Now that we have successfully parsed the input data, I'll proceed with the next step - validating the data using the data_processing_validator. Since we don't have a specific schema, I'll use a generic schema that validates basic JSON structure.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator {
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "array",
        "items": {
          "type": "object"
        }
      }
    },
    "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": "data/input.json"
}</tool_call>

I'll adjust the transformation parameters to specify JSON-to-JSON transformation since the error indicates it expected CSV format but we're working with JSON data.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer {
  "input_format": "json",
  "output_format": "json",
  "options": {
    "input_type": "json",
    "output_type": "json"
  },
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "destination": "data/transformed.json"
}</tool_call>

            Now that the data has been validated and transformed, I'll proceed with the final step - filtering unnecessary elements using the data_processing_filter tool.

<tool_call>data_processing_filter {
  "source": "data/transformed.json",
  "destination": "data/output.json",
  "options": {
    "filter_fields": ["metadata", "temporary_data"],
    "keep_required": true
  }
}</tool_call>
